etymologies: late 17th century. From French chambranle, probably an alteration (by folk-etymological association with branler to shake, although the semantic motivation is unclear) of chambrande from an unattested post-classical Latin form *camerandus or its neuter singular *camerandum, use as noun of gerundive of post-classical Latin camerare, thus lit. ‘something which must be arched’. See further Trésor de la langue française at cited word

definitions: An ornamental frame around the top and sides of a door, window, or fireplace.
